Reasoning: 
1. cs.IT (Information Theory) - The paper deals with the degrees of freedom (DoF) of interference and X channels, which is a fundamental concept in information theory. 
2. cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) - The paper proposes transmission schemes for interference and X channels, which are relevant to networking and internet architecture. 
3. cs.SI (Systems and Control) - The paper considers delayed channel state information (CSI) and proposes distributed interference management, which are topics related to systems and control. 
4. cs.MM (Multimedia) - The paper proposes higher order symbol generation, which is relevant to multimedia applications. 
5. cs.CE (Computational Engineering, Finance, and Science) - The paper proposes novel transmission schemes, which may have computational implications in engineering, finance, and science.
